useRef is a React Hook that lets you:

Access DOM elements directly.
Store values that persist between renders without causing re-renders.
1. Syntax
import { useRef } from "react";

function Example() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  return (
    <input ref={inputRef} />
  );
}
useRef() returns an object.
The object contains a property called current.
inputRef.current
2. Focusing an Input
Example
import { useRef } from "react";

function InputFocus() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const focusInput = () => {
    inputRef.current.focus();
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="text"
        ref={inputRef}
        placeholder="Enter name"
      />

      <button onClick={focusInput}>
        Focus Input
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default InputFocus;
How it works
React creates a reference object.
ref={inputRef} connects the input element to the ref.
The actual DOM element is stored in:
inputRef.current
Calling:
inputRef.current.focus();

moves the cursor into the input box.

3. Clearing an Input
import { useRef } from "react";

function ClearInput() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const clearText = () => {
    inputRef.current.value = "";
  };

  return (
    <>
      <input ref={inputRef} />
      <button onClick={clearText}>Clear</button>
    </>
  );
}

export default ClearInput;
4. Storing Values Without Re-rendering

Unlike useState, changing a ref does not re-render the component.

import { useRef } from "react";

function Counter() {
  const countRef = useRef(0);

  const increment = () => {
    countRef.current++;
    console.log(countRef.current);
  };

  return (
    <button onClick={increment}>
      Increment
    </button>
  );
}

export default Counter;
Difference
useState
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

setCount(count + 1);

✅ Re-renders component

useRef
countRef.current++;

❌ Does not re-render component

5. Previous Value Example
import { useState, useEffect, useRef } from "react";

function PreviousCount() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const prevCount = useRef();

  useEffect(() => {
    prevCount.current = count;
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Current: {count}</p>
      <p>Previous: {prevCount.current}</p>

      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increment
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default PreviousCount;
useRef vs useState
Feature	useRef	useState
Stores value	✅	✅
Persists between renders	✅	✅
Causes re-render	❌	✅
Access DOM elements	✅	❌
Common Interview Questions
1. What is useRef?

A React Hook that stores mutable values and provides direct access to DOM elements without causing re-renders.

2. Does updating useRef trigger a re-render?

No.

ref.current = 10;

will not re-render the component.

3. When should you use useRef?
Focusing inputs
Accessing DOM elements
Storing timers/interval IDs
Storing previous values
Holding mutable data without re-rendering
